@Node "SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS" 
@Next "FEATURES"
@Prev "DISCLAIMER"
@Toc "Main"

SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS

   o an Amiga computer (or compatible) with any 680X0 processor.

   o OS3.0 or higher (perhaps does it work with OS2.0, but I can't tell).

   o asl.library (because of Blitz's ASL requesters).

   o enough Chip RAM to open a window on the WorkBench screen.

   o the "Japanese" system patch by Marcus Lundblad, available from aminet://text/misc/japanese.lha.

   o enough RAM to run the patch and Kezaco at the same time

   o it'd be fine if you put KEZACO on a hard disk

   o if you want to use all Kanji dictionary search, put those files on your disk too :
      -edict    (available via ftp at the Monash university...
      -kanjidic  I can't find the adress for now, but it's something like #?.monash.edu.au)
      -edict.xjdx
      -kanjidic.xjdx
      (if you can't find #?.xjdx files, get #?.jdx files and use my converter availabe from
      aminet://text/misc/Jdx2Xjdx.lha)

   o muFS if you want to be identified by KEZACO... but it is of no use...

  The smallest machine on which I tried KEZACO is a standard A1200HD, I tried disabling AGA, 
and it still worked, even without FastMem...
  The biggest machine on which I tried KEZACO is fully non-standard Pentium166 running UAE,
and it worked, even without a properly installed WorkBench.

  It is developed on a Blizzard1230@50MHz A1200 with 1Gb muFS+AFS HD, Creative HexSpeed 
atapi CD-ROM, 2Mb ChipMem, 16Mb FastMem, KS39.106, WB40.35, 3-5 bitplanes WB.

@EndNode

@Node "FEATURES" 
@Next "GETTING STARTED"
@Prev "SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS"
@Toc "Main"

FEATURES

   o It's a Commodity

   o it has AppWindow/AppIcon and AppMenuItem

   o it is useable from either WorkBench or CLI

   o its config is in the tooltypes

   o ASCII, Kana and Kanji input

   o dictionary lookup

   o it is able to open multiple JIS and EUC documents

   o it saves JIS or EUC documents

   o it uses the real Amiga Clipboard device

@EndNode

@Node "GETTING STARTED" 
@Next "INSTRUCTIONS"
@Prev "FEATURES"
@Toc "Main"

GETTING STARTED

You just lha-x-ed the Kezaco archive...

Hum...

To run KEZACO from WorkBench :

 1) starting with an empty document

      -Click twice on the KEZACO icon
      -Well done !

 2) starting with a jis/sjis file without default tool type "KEZACO" :

      -Click one on the KEZACO icon
      -Shift-double-click on the file

 3) starting with a jis/sjis file with the default tool type set as "KEZACO" (and its pathway) :

      -Double-click on the file's icon

To run KEZACO from a shell :

 1) with an empty document :

      -type 'KEZACO'
      -press return

 2) opening a jis/sjis file :

      -type 'KEZACO'
      -press space
      -type the file's name
      -press return

  Now read the chapter called INSTRUCTIONS !

@EndNode

@Node "INSTRUCTIONS" 
@Next "COMPATIBLITY"
@Prev "GETTING STARTED"
@Toc "Main"

INSTRUCTIONS

  I won't explain you how to use everything, because it is quite trivial.

  I'll only explain the main priciples, and the things that aren't perfectly standard.


  1. Entering text
   When you enter text, it's following an 'input mode', here is how they each work

   1.0 Moving the cursor
     Just use the cursor keys.  If you press CTRL+cursor, you'll go to the begin/end of the line/text.
     If you press ALT+cursor, you'll advance to the next/previous space/page.
     If you press SHIFT+cursor, you'll select text.

   1.1 ASCII
     Just type in your text normally, I mean : press the 'A' key, and a 'a' will appear.
     Use shift for upper case !!

   1.2 Kana
     Just type in your text as if it was written in rﮪmaji.  What you type is displayed
     in the windows' title bar.
     Type in upper case to get katakanas, lower case for hiraganas.

     Example :
      'chi' will display the hiragana pronounced 'chi' (۳ﭼ)
      'TA'  will display the katakana pronounced 'ta' (۴ﺟ)
      'nya' will display the hiragana 'ni' and the small hiragana 'ya' (۳ﺯ۳ﻙ)
      'DI'  will display the katakana 'de' and the small katakana 'i' (۴ﮄ۴۲)
      'ppa' will display the small hiragana 'tsu' and the hiragana 'pa' (۳ﺣ۳ﺹ)
      'VA' will display the new katakana notation of such sounds (۴ﮪ۴۰)
      Understood ?

      Typing '+a' will give you the small hiragana 'a' alone, and so on... (even '+KA' works !)۰۰(۳۰۰۰۴ﺀ)

     If you put a '$' before your string, and terminate it with another '$', KEZACO will try
     to find a kanji equivalent using edict and the verb inflection table. (See dictionary)

     If you put a "tick" (`) before and after your string, KEZACO will try to find a kanji
     equivalent using the Wnn files... It's much faster, but less precise.  It will display a
     choice of kanji in the title bar.  The currently selected is the seperated one on the left.
     If you press "tick" again, the list will scroll left.
     If you press "tilde" (~), the list will scroll right.
     If you press "space", the first kana will be skipped.
     If you press "return", the current kanji will be inserted into the text, AND
      the rest of the input will be "re-ticked".
     If you press another key, the current kanji will only be inserted into the text.
     (Example : `watashihanihonjin'`, press "tick" again to select ﭨﻛ, then press
      "return" to accept the kanji and convert the rest of the input : "hanihonjin'".
      "ha" isn't to be converted into a kanji, so, press space.  Then press tick to
      select ﺩﮰﺯﻎﺟﺱ and then press any other key to accept the string.)

   1.3 J-Map
     It's an attempt of a Japanese keymap simulation...
     (it has been sent to me by JR Cos (xrc@nil.fut.es)
۰۰۰۰۰۰۲ﺎ۰۰۲ﺎ۰۰۲ﺏ۰۰۲ﺑ۰۰۲ﭖ۰۰۲ﭘ۰۰۲ﺓ۰۰۲ﺕ۰۰۲ﺗ۰۰۲ﺍ۰۰۰ﻏ۰۰۰ﻕ۰۰۰ﭺ
۰۰۰۰۰۰۳ﮊ۰۰۳ﻁ۰۰۳۱۰۰۳۵۰۰۳۷۰۰۳۹۰۰۳ﻛ۰۰۳ﮔ۰۰۳ﻟ۰۰۳ﺅ۰۰۳ﻍ۰۰۳ﻊ۰۰۰ﺙ
۰۰۰۰۰۰۲ﺹ۰۰۲ﻉ۰۰۲ﺧ۰۰۲ﺻ۰۰۲ﺿ۰۰۲ﻋ۰۰۲ﻁ۰۰۲ﺭ۰۰۲ﺵ۰۰۲ﺷ۰۰۰ﺳ۰۰۰ﺵ
۰۰۰۰۰۰۳ﺟ۰۰۳ﺩ۰۰۳۳۰۰۳ﺗ۰۰۳،۰۰۳ﮩ۰۰۳ﮌ۰۰۳ﺯ۰۰۳ﻠ۰۰۳ﭨ۰۰۰،۰۰۰؛
۰۰۰۰۰۰۲ﭼ۰۰۲ﺽ۰۰۲ﺥ۰۰۲ﺩ۰۰۲ﮄ۰۰۲ﺫ۰۰۲ﮌ۰۰۲ﺯ۰۰۲ﮊ۰۰۰۷۰۰۰ﮞ۰۰۰ﻲ
۰۰۰۰۰۰۳ﭼ۰۰۳ﺫ۰۰۳ﺓ۰۰۳ﺵ۰۰۳­۰۰۳ﺁ۰۰۳ﻐ۰۰۳ﺳ۰۰۳ﻡ۰۰۳ﮞ۰۰۳ﺎ۰۰۳ﻓ
۰۰۰۰۰۰۲ﻌ۰۰۲ﻊ۰۰۲ﺣ۰۰۲ﻅ۰۰۲ﺡ۰۰۲ﺳ۰۰۲ﺱ۰۰۰۳۰۰۰۴۰۰۰ﺟ۰۰۰ﻲ
۰۰۰۰۰۰۳ﺥ۰۰۳ﭖ۰۰۳ﺛ۰۰۳ﺻ۰۰۳ﺏ۰۰۳ﻑ۰۰۳ﻗ۰۰۳ﺱ۰۰۳ﻣ۰۰۳ﻕ۰۰۳ﻥ
      Maybe you'll want to make some stickers to put on your keyboard...
      The ۰ﻲ keys, are non-QWERTY keys.  But, if you have a keyboard which
      has those, they'll be supported.  Else, they'll be on the numeric keypad's 1 and 4.
      "But, how do I get katakanas ???"
      Easy : turn Caps Lock on.
      "How do I get ۳؛۳ﻅ۴ﺽ and such things ?"
      Press left or right shift.
      "How do I get ۴ﻉ۳ﺹ۳ﺣ۳۰ ?"
      Press control !!
      (I had to add this, because on my keymap (f : azerty), the key beside P is already
      a "dead key" used for accents, and it didn't return an event when I pressed it...
      So, I also added that key on the Help key...)
      Plus : the usually missing bottom key is also mirrored on the other side of the
      keyboard on the f:<> key, which also exists on the e keyboards, and perhaps
      elsewhere too...
      "How do I get kanjis in J-Map mode ?"
      Use the ` key before and after (like $ in Kana mode).  (` is the key left of 1 on my keymap)

   1.4 Meaning
     Type in the english word you want to match, then press '$'

   1.5 JIS
     Type in the two characters that are the jis code of the kanji

   1.6 Code (only if kjdic is available)
     Type in the wanted code and press return

     Codes are like said in the kanjdic.doc file, if you've lost it, there are the usefulest ones

     'Sn' where n is number of strokes
     'Bn" where n is the bushu index code

     'Pa-b-c' where :
        a is the kanji type :
             1 : split left/right
             2 : split top/bottom
             3 : split inside/out
             4 : one part

        b is the number of strokes in the first part (whole kanji if a=4)

        c is the number of strokes in the second part (if a=1 2 3)

             a code if a=4 : 1 it has a horizontal line on the top
                             2                                 bottom
                             3          vertical line in the middle from top to bottom
                             4 none of above

     Using those P-codes is very useful when you don't know how to pronounce a kanji.

   1.7 LookUp
     It isn't really an input mode, it tries to find in the dictionary the next N characters
     (from the pointer position), N being the number you press.

   1.8 HexJIS
     Type in the 4 hex digits of the wanted kanji.

       Example : HexJIS:3021 is the same as JIS:0!   ^_^;

  2. Marking blocs
    Select an area with the mouse, or shift-cursor.

  3. Find 'n' Replace
    First set the Find and/or the Replace string(s) : select them in a bloc and use the menu.
    Then use Next to find next and replace to replace.

  4. The Preferences... hum...
    Sorry... they are disabled in the current version... but I'll do it later... (I know... I already said that
    two years ago v_v...)  You just have to modify the tooltypes :
       EDict= the filename of your edict file
       KJDic= the filename of your kanjidic file
       MuDir= the filename of your MultiUser command directory
       MaxLines= the maximum number of lines your documents will be able to have
       MaxDoc= the maximum number of documents you'll edit at the same time
       CX_POPKEY= the commodity hotkey
       InputKeys= the 8 shortcuts to change input mode, in this order :
          ASCII,Kana,J-Map,Meaning,Code,Jis,LookUp,HexJis
       Dollar= the unused key near return on YOUR keyboard
       Star= shift+the previous key
       Tick= the key under escape and above tab on YOUR keyboard
       Tilde= shift+the previous key
       BigFont= the font you want to be used IN the windows (ex:geneva.font)
       BigFontSize= the size of the font (ex:16)
       MediumFont= the font you want to be used in MENUES and TITLE BAR (ex:xen.font)
       MediumFontSize= the size of this font (ex:8)
       DictBuffer= the number of entries the dictionary window will have simultaneously
       
  5. Looking for kanjis
    The JIS Table allows you to browse through the font.  Everything is in the menu, but
    the keys are : cursors, escape to exit, Amiga+'g' for goto

    The Bitmap Matching system has been removed.

    The Kanji Seek is done now, it allows you to tell Kezaco the number of strokes of the kanji,
    and/or indicate some of the shapes that compose it.  Then Kezaco gives you a list of all corresponding
    kanjis (like JWP does with its Radical Lookup)
    The '+', '-' and 's' keys allow you to set the number of strokes.
    The 'c' key clears all selected shapes.
    The 'backspace' key removes the last selected shape from the description.
    The 'tick' and 'tilde' keys allow you to browse through to the possible kanjis.
    The 'return' key puts the selected kanji into the text.

  6. Special things...
    Most is documented in the history part...  I hope you'll find everything, because
    I don't want to read this guide again, looking after what's missing...

    The BitmapCursor tooltype doesn't mean anything anymore.
   
@EndNode

@Node "COMPATIBLITY" 
@Next "TO DO"
@Prev "INSTRUCTIONS"
@Toc "Main"

COMPATIBLITY

  KEZACO can only read JIS and EUC files.

  Trying to load JWP files might be fun... never tried, but KEZACO might be going nuts after
  that... I guess all control characters from JWP will be understood as ASCII strings...

  The Save options allow you to save Old JIS or EUC files, select the file format in the Special menu.

@EndNode

