HISTORY

June'96

  I put a first version of KEZACO on AmiNet... it didn't much thing...
  the only thing that really worked was the Kana input mode, and the file loading.


July'96

  That version nearly worked... but there was an horrible bug :

  I was scanning through the index files with the Blitz2 'Edit$()' command... so
  it gave me something weird each time a character Line Feed appeared !!

  When I understood the bug, I thought it was time for me to read the instructions.


August'96

  This version is very safe !!!

  I still don't know why it crashed yesterday... so, just save often enough, and if
  it crashes, mail me the circumstances.  I hope I'll be able to fix this later.

  There now are Find/Replace, Cut/Copy/Paste, many LookUps...

  The file 'Madrigal.jis' is still included, those are the lyrics of the track 4 of
  a CD called 'MADRIGAL', sung by Hiroko Kasahara, and which I listened a lot since
  the beginning of coding KEZACO.


  First users reported bugs and needed improvements.

  ...so is the menu font problem fixed ! (but not the palette problem... and I still
  can't find what's going wrong !!)

  There is a new HexJIS input mode.

  KEZACO was saving one line too much... oops... it has now been corrected

  Facultative ToolTypes Dollar=$ and Star=* to select other keys, it was thought in the
  idea that $ was the nearest key to 'return' on the second row, and * was shift-$.
  If you don't use those tooltypes, old $ and * will be used instead.

  You may force old-jis format in load, thanks to the new "special" menu.  But then,
  the characters with ascii codes over 127 won't be printed... this is because I'm
  using built-in Blitz2 strings, and their Print command, and that only supports
  ascii-7 characters...  I'll have to rewrite a big part of the program before that it
  works properly with latin-1...  v_v;


September'96

  Kyaaaa !  I was looking in the OS3.0 autodocs to find how to create a slider which
  is in the window border... and I didn't find that... I only found that I forgot to
  put the 'NewLookMenu' flag when opening the window...  so, I corrected the menu
  appearance...

  Another thing, if the filename is '#?.html#?' it will be saved in EUC.  It isn't
  very great, but it was for an easy immediate use.

  Anyway... I still don't know how to create sliders (in window borders)...
  By now, I could put one, but it'll be inside the window, as any gadget.  This looks
  ugly.


October'96

  It's 28 october today... and I just began to work again on Kezaco... I'm really sorry.
  I've got many problems which made me unable to continue working earlier...  First,
  I tried the new fMSX... and I played Konami's "Parodius" a little too much, but I
  couldn't get through the first level, and to 'continue' after game over, you have
  to 'hit' the 'F5' key... but after retrying agin and again, I got angry and hit the
  'F5' key very hard... the only problem is that I own a A1200... this caused some
  harddisk problems, and I'm working with AFS (patched with muFS !!) and there's no tool
  yet to get anything back after that kind of crash, but I managed to get nearly all
  my damaged files back... then there has been another problem, I've bought Team17's
  'Killing Grounds' ^_^;; and I had to complete it before doing anything else...  (I
  did it with the cheats, else would it last one more year...)  So, now, I'm ready to
  return to work !!  That's what I did today with the new Kana function !  (You won't
  see any difference, but it's going a lot faster than before : before it parsed
  nearly 300 entries twice each time you pressed a key, but now is it put in a far
  faster structure which makes it much faster.)
  Another thing is the 'PiCross'-menu entry... it won't do a thing, except if you look
  at the file t:PiCross which will contain a PiCross description of a kanji : line per
  line first, then column by column...  I forgot to remove it from the distributed
  version... but it's only 1Kb long.
  Next month, I hope I'll be able to add some kanji-bitmap buffering, and dictionnary
  search buffering too.  (I've got some courses about optimisation, and it is of much
  help.)

  Two days later...
  A user told me earlier version didn't even start !!  Well, I think it's corrected now.
  It was because of trying to load a font whose name was in the Env:sys/font.prefs file,
  but it seems that this file hasn't always the same format...  anyway, I only loaded
  it to give the menues the good font... but now, trying to load a default topaz 8 if
  wanted by the user, I remarked that my menues had got the correct font !!!
  So now, it only 'reads' the standard topaz 8, even if it doesn't use it ! (no problem,
  it's a romfont)
  As problem often appear only with some people, if your menues now are back with topaz,
  then, I think you should warn me, and I'd have to finally add that 'ForceTopaz'
  tooltype !


November 1996

  Some users didn't find the 'mouse-cursor' idea very good... so, there now is a bitmap
  cursor possibility...  It doesn't look very pretty, but it may be of some use, I guess
  that moving the mouse pointer didn't work well on some graphic cards... sorry...
  I should have done it nicely with a mask, and so on... but it would have slowed the
  display down...  this way, the speeds stays correct.
  To activate this option, add the tooltype : "BitmapCursor=1".

January 1997

  Oops... I completely forgot to edit the guide on that time... so I don't remember
  what has been improved since previous version.  But anyway, it doesn't make things
  worse than before...  I think I tried to fix an awful bug : it crashed when you
  asked to insert too long dictionary lines...  but I hadn't been able to fix it...
  Just say your lines are maximum 125 characters (or something like this...) it should
  be working almost all the time...
  The crash happens when there are too many pronounciations available.
  Never forget the one big rule : save as often as possible.

February 1997

  Nothing new... but I'll finally put version 1.54 on AmiNet tomorrow.  It will be
  released with the ashiya24 font this time.  That's all.

  If there are some example files... they'll sure be lyrics of songs from
  Hisakawa Aya's "for you for me" album.


September 1997

  It's been a long time since I wrote anything in Kezaco...
  I've added the Wnn-"tick" input : put ticks (`) around your Kana input, and Kezaco looks in the Wnn database
  if she finds anything pronounced that way.  Then she shows possible kanjis in the title bar.
  Pressing "tick" (`) and "tilde" (~) scrolls through the kanjis, pressing another key inserts the current
  kanji into the text.

  I also corrected something that made the dictionary crash sometimes.

  Separately, I've written a routine able to find kanjis knowing the number of strokes and informations about
  the shapes contained in it.  But I still have to write an interface to include it in Kezaco.  If I am fast enough,
  it will be done tomorrow and you will never see this text. (ﺝﺷ)

  I'm thinking of writing some vague translation/teach routines.  Does anyone think it is a good idea ?

  For the first time, I completed the old guide to match Kezaco-2, and I did it using Kezaco-2 herself !

The day after...
  Okay !  The Kanji Seek is done... well, it's not very good looking, but it works.

  I also added some little things to the Wnn-tick thing :
    -return re-ticks the rest
    -space skips one kana
(ex: `watashihanihonjin'`, accept "watashi" and press return.
      `hanihonjin'`, press space to skip the particle,
      `nihonjin`, accept "nihonjin".  Pretty useful, ne ?)

  The "licence-agreement" terms are going to change... because I'm afraid something
  may happen...


October 1997

  I only corrected a few display bugs... it's still far from perfect, but at least, window borders
  aren't erased anymore... ^_^
  The cut/copy/paste is now done from and to the real Amiga Clipboard device.


December 1997

  I partially fixed the dictionary search strange behaviour.
  I really should rewrite the dictionary routine one more time...

----
  KEZACO is still a program, but it will sure one day become a 'she', (you know, the
  same way Pinocchio became a boy)... then we'll call her 'Kezako-chan' ^_^;;

  I've thought a little... After Kezaco-2... it will be Kezaco-3 : Kezaco-san !  She'll have to be much more
  user friendly then...

@EndNode

